{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17614412","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17614412"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T14:44:48+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T14:44:48+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16365"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16365","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16365"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.84,0,0.05,0.05,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9056"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114485"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9056"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16365"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96486"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"2273"},{"type":"tags","id":"4911"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7178"},{"type":"tags","id":"7184"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21532"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21535"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114485","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114485"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe sympathetic nerve supply to the eye and face travels a complex pathway from the hypothalamus, through the brainstem and cervical region, ultimately accompanying the internal carotid artery through the neck and cavernous sinus.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the clinical features that result from disruption of sympathetic fibres along the internal carotid artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Miosis, ptosis, and facial anhidrosis","Mydriasis, ptosis, and facial flushing","Miosis, lid retraction, and facial sweating","Mydriasis, lid retraction, and facial anhidrosis","Miosis, ptosis, and facial sweating"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDisruption of sympathetic fibres along the internal carotid artery results in Horner Syndrome, characterised by the triad of \u003Cstrong\u003Emiosis, ptosis, and facial anhidrosis\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs because miosis represents a constricted pupil due to unopposed parasympathetic activity, ptosis involves drooping of the upper eyelid due to paralysis of the superior tarsal muscle also known as M\u00fcller\u0027s muscle (a sympathetically innervated muscle), and facial anhidrosis represents loss of sweating on the ipsilateral side of the face, occurring when the lesion involves sympathetic fibers before they diverge to the sweat glands.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMydriasis, ptosis, and facial flushing\u003C/strong\u003E would not occur together as mydriasis indicates sympathetic overactivity whilst ptosis suggests sympathetic underactivity. \u003Cstrong\u003EMiosis, lid retraction, and facial sweating\u003C/strong\u003E combines features of both sympathetic underactivity (miosis) and overactivity (lid retraction and sweating). \u003Cstrong\u003EMydriasis, lid retraction, and facial anhidrosis\u003C/strong\u003E represents a mixed pattern that does not correspond to any recognised clinical syndrome. \u003Cstrong\u003EMiosis, ptosis, and facial sweating\u003C/strong\u003E includes the correct pupillary and eyelid findings but facial sweating would be reduced rather than present in sympathetic disruption.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Horner syndrome consists of the triad of miosis, ptosis, and facial anhidrosis due to disruption of sympathetic innervation.","The sympathetic pathway to the eye and face travels alongside the internal carotid artery through the cavernous sinus.","Second-order (preganglionic) sympathetic neurons synapse in the superior cervical ganglion before third-order fibers follow the internal carotid artery."],"references":["Sabbagh MA, De Lott LB, Trobe JD. Causes of Horner Syndrome: A Study of 318 Patients. J Neuroophthalmol. 2020 Sep;40(3):362-369. doi: 10.1097/WNO.0000000000000844. PMID: 31609831; PMCID: PMC7148177.","Khan Z, Bollu PC. Horner Syndrome. 2023 Apr 10. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 29763176.","Martin TJ. Horner Syndrome: A Clinical Review. ACS Chem Neurosci. 2018 Feb 21;9(2):177-186. doi: 10.1021/acschemneuro.7b00405. Epub 2017 Dec 20. PMID: 29260849."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96486"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16365"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96486","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/96486"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-16T21:05:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-16T21:05:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9056"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114485"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"d